# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: confluence-rewriting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] In lambda calculus, the **Church–Rosser theorem** states that, when applying reduction rules to terms, the ordering in which the reductions are chosen does not make a difference to the eventual result.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] More precisely, if there are two distinct reductions or sequences of reductions that can be applied to the same term, then there exists a term that is reachable from both results, by applying (possibly empty) sequences of additional reductions.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The theorem was proved in 1936 by Alonzo Church and J.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The theorem is symbolized by the adjacent diagram: If term *a* can be reduced to both *b* and *c*, then there must be a further term *d* (possibly equal to either *b* or *c*) to which both *b* and *c* can be reduced.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] Viewing the lambda calculus as an abstract rewriting system, the Church–Rosser theorem states that the reduction rules of the lambda calculus are confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] As a consequence of the theorem, a term in the lambda calculus has at most one normal form, justifying reference to "*the* normal form" of a given normalizable term.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] Barkley Rosser proved that the theorem holds for β-reduction in the λI-calculus (in which every abstracted variable must appear in the term's body).
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The proof method is known as "finiteness of developments", and it has additional consequences such as the Standardization Theorem, which relates to a method in which reductions can be performed from left to right to reach a normal form (if one exists).
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The result for the pure untyped lambda calculus was proved by D.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] One type of reduction in the pure untyped lambda calculus for which the Church–Rosser theorem applies is β-reduction, in which a subterm of the form $(\lambda x.t)s$ is contracted by the substitution $t[x:=s]$ , where $t,s$ are two lambda expressions.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The theorem also applies to η-reduction, in which a subterm $\lambda x.Sx$ is replaced by S .
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] It also applies to βη-reduction, the union of the two reduction rules.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] For β-reduction, one proof method originates from William W.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] Then the Church–Rosser property is the statement that $\twoheadrightarrow _{\beta }$ satisfies the diamond property.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] We introduce a new reduction $\rightarrow _{\|}$ whose reflexive transitive closure is $\twoheadrightarrow _{\beta }$ and which satisfies the diamond property.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] By induction on the number of steps in the reduction, it thus follows that $\twoheadrightarrow _{\beta }$ satisfies the diamond property.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The η-reduction rule can be proved to be Church–Rosser directly.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] Hence we can conclude that βη-reduction is Church–Rosser.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] The Church–Rosser theorem also holds for many variants of the lambda calculus, such as the simply typed lambda calculus, many calculi with advanced type systems, and Gordon Plotkin's beta-value calculus.
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] Plotkin also used a Church–Rosser theorem to prove that the evaluation of functional programs (for both lazy evaluation and eager evaluation) is a function from programs to values (a subset of the lambda terms).
[src:confluence-rewriting/church-rosser-theorem] In older research papers, a rewriting system is said to be Church–Rosser, or to have the Church–Rosser property, when it is confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] In computer science and mathematics, **confluence** is a property of rewriting systems, describing which terms in such a system can be rewritten in more than one way, to yield the same result.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] This article describes the properties in the most abstract setting of an abstract rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] The usual rules of elementary arithmetic form an abstract rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] For example, the expression (11 + 9) × (2 + 4) can be evaluated starting either at the left or at the right parentheses; however, in both cases the same result is eventually obtained.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If every arithmetic expression evaluates to the same result regardless of reduction strategy, the arithmetic rewriting system is said to be ground-confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Arithmetic rewriting systems may be confluent or only ground-confluent depending on details of the rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] This proof starts from the given group axioms A1–A3, and establishes five propositions R4, R6, R10, R11, and R12, each of them using some earlier ones, and R12 being the main theorem.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Some of the proofs require non-obvious, or even creative, steps, like applying axiom A2 in reverse, thereby rewriting "1" to "*a*−1 ⋅ a" in the first step of R6's proof.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] One of the historical motivations to develop the *theory of term rewriting* was to avoid the need for such steps, which are difficult to find by an inexperienced human, let alone by a computer program .
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If a term rewriting system is confluent and *terminating*, a straightforward method exists to prove equality between two expressions (also known as *terms*) *s* and *t*: Starting with *s*, apply equalities from left to right as long as possible, eventually obtaining a term *s′*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Obtain from *t* a term *t′* in a similar way.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If both terms *s′* and *t′* literally agree, then *s* and *t* are proven equal.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] More importantly, if they disagree, then *s* and *t* cannot be equal.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] That is, any two terms *s* and *t* that can be proven equal at all can be done so by that method.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Therefore, if a confluent and terminating term rewriting system can be provided for some equational theory, not a tinge of creativity is required to perform proofs of term equality; that task hence becomes amenable to computer programs.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Modern approaches handle more general *abstract rewriting systems* rather than *term* rewriting systems; the latter are a special case of the former.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system can be expressed as a directed graph in which nodes represent expressions and edges represent rewrites.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] So, for example, if the expression *a* can be rewritten into *b*, then we say that *b* is a *reduct* of *a* (alternatively, *a* *reduces to* *b*, or *a* is an *expansion* of *b*).
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] This is represented using arrow notation; *a* → *b* indicates that *a* reduces to *b*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Intuitively, this means that the corresponding graph has a directed edge from *a* to *b*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If there is a path between two graph nodes *c* and *d*, then it forms a *reduction sequence*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] So, for instance, if *c* → *c′* → *c′′* → ... → *d′* → *d*, then we can write *c* ∗→ *d*, indicating the existence of a reduction sequence from *c* to *d*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Formally, ∗→ is the reflexive-transitive closure of →.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] With this established, confluence can be defined as follows.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If every *a* ∈ *S* is confluent, we say that → is confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] This property is also sometimes called the *diamond property*, after the shape of the diagram shown on the right.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Some authors reserve the term *diamond property* for a variant of the diagram with single reductions everywhere; that is, whenever *a* → *b* and *a* → *c*, there must exist a *d* such that *b* → *d* and *c* → *d*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] The single-reduction variant is strictly stronger than the multi-reduction one.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A term rewriting system is **ground confluent** if every ground term is confluent, that is, every term without variables.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] An element *a* ∈ *S* is said to be **locally confluent** (or *weakly confluent*) if for all *b*, *c* ∈ *S* with *a* → *b* and *a* → *c* there exists *d* ∈ *S* with *b* ∗→ *d* and *c* ∗→ *d*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] If every *a* ∈ *S* is locally confluent, then → is called locally confluent, or having the *weak Church–Rosser property*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] This is different from confluence in that *b* and *c* must be reduced from *a* in one step.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] In analogy with this, confluence is sometimes referred to as *global confluence*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] The relation ∗→, introduced as a notation for reduction sequences, may be viewed as a rewriting system in its own right, whose relation is the reflexive-transitive closure of *→*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Since a sequence of reduction sequences is again a reduction sequence (or, equivalently, since forming the reflexive-transitive closure is idempotent), ∗∗→ = ∗→.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] It follows that → is confluent if and only if ∗→ is locally confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system may be locally confluent without being (globally) confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] However, Newman's lemma states that if a locally confluent rewriting system has no infinite reduction sequences (in which case it is said to be *terminating* or *strongly normalizing*), then it is globally confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system is said to possess the **Church–Rosser property** if and only if $x{\stackrel {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ implies $x{\mathbin {\downarrow }}y$ for all objects *x*, *y*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Barkley Rosser proved in 1936 that lambda calculus has this property; hence the name of the property.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] (The fact that lambda calculus has this property is also known as the Church–Rosser theorem.) In a rewriting system with the Church–Rosser property the word problem may be reduced to the search for a common successor.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] In a Church–Rosser system, an object has *at most one* normal form; that is the normal form of an object is unique if it exists, but it may well not exist.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] In lambda calculus for instance, the expression (λx.xx)(λx.xx) does not have a normal form because there exists an infinite sequence of β-reductions (λx.xx)(λx.xx) → (λx.xx)(λx.xx) → ...
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system possesses the Church–Rosser property if and only if it is confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Because of this equivalence, a fair bit of variation in definitions is encountered in the literature.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] For instance, in "Terese" the Church–Rosser property and confluence are defined to be synonymous and identical to the definition of confluence presented here; Church–Rosser as defined here remains unnamed, but is given as an equivalent property; this departure from other texts is deliberate.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] The definition of local confluence differs from that of global confluence in that only elements reached from a given element in a single rewriting step are considered.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A semi-confluent element need not be confluent, but a semi-confluent rewriting system is necessarily confluent, and a confluent system is trivially semi-confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] Strong confluence is another variation on local confluence that allows us to conclude that a rewriting system is globally confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] An element *a* ∈ *S* is said to be **strongly confluent** if for all *b*, *c* ∈ *S* with *a* → *b* and *a* → *c* there exists *d* ∈ *S* with *b* ∗→ *d* and either *c* → *d* or *c* = *d*; if every *a* ∈ *S* is strongly confluent, we say that → is strongly confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/confluence-abstract-rewriting] A confluent element need not be strongly confluent, but a strongly confluent rewriting system is necessarily confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] In theoretical computer science, specifically in term rewriting, **Newman's lemma**, also commonly called the **diamond lemma**, is a criterion to prove that an abstract rewriting system is confluent.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] It states that local confluence is a sufficient condition for confluence, provided that the system is also terminating.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] This is useful since local confluence is usually easier to verify than confluence.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] The lemma was originally proved by Max Newman in 1942.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] A considerably simpler proof (given below) was proposed by Gérard Huet.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] The lemma is purely combinatorial and applies to any relation.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] Because $\to$ is terminating, we can perform well-founded induction on u along $\to$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] where the dotted arrows represent sequences of arbitrarily many reductions by $\to$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] Base case: If $u=v$ or $u=w$ , this is trivial.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] A related result was shown by Kimmo Eriksson in 1993.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] Recall that an abstract rewriting system is locally confluent if for any two reductions $a\to b$ and $a\to c$ , there exists d such that $b\to ^{*}d$ and $c\to ^{*}d$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] If additionally it is required that the reduction chains $b\to ^{*}d$ and $c\to ^{*}d$ have the same length, then the system is said to have the **polygon property**.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] Examples of rewriting systems with the polygon property include bubble sort and the chip-firing game.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] By Newman's lemma, the system is confluent, and every element has a unique normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] For each element u , define $rl(u)$ be the length of the *shortest* reduction chain from u to its normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] If $rl(u)=0$ , then u is already in normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/diamond-lemma] Otherwise, $rl(u)\geq 1$ , and we apply the polygonal property and the induction hypothesis.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] In abstract rewriting, an object is in **normal form** if it cannot be rewritten any further, i.e. it is irreducible.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Depending on the rewriting system, an object may rewrite to several normal forms or none at all.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Many properties of rewriting systems relate to normal forms.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Stated formally, if (*A*,→) is an abstract rewriting system, *x*∈*A* is in **normal form** if no *y*∈*A* exists such that *x*→*y*, i.e.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] An object *a* is **weakly normalizing** if there exists at least one particular sequence of rewrites starting from *a* that eventually yields a normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the **weak normalization property** or is *(weakly) normalizing* (WN) if every object is weakly normalizing.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] An object *a* is **strongly normalizing** if every sequence of rewrites starting from *a* eventually terminates with a normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system is *strongly normalizing*, *terminating*, *noetherian*, or has the **(strong) normalization property** (SN), if each of its objects is strongly normalizing.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *normal form property* (NF) if for all objects *a* and normal forms *b*, *b* can be reached from *a* by a series of rewrites and inverse rewrites only if *a* reduces to *b*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *unique normal form property* (UN) if for all normal forms *a*, *b* ∈ *S*, *a* can be reached from *b* by a series of rewrites and inverse rewrites only if *a* is equal to *b*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *unique normal form property with respect to reduction* (UN→) if for every term reducing to normal forms *a* and *b*, *a* is equal to *b*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] This section presents some well known results.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Confluence (abbreviated CR) implies NF implies UN implies UN→.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Hence CR, NF, UN, and UN→ coincide if WN holds.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] One example is that simplifying arithmetic expressions produces a number - in arithmetic, all numbers are normal forms.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Examples of non-normalizing systems (not weakly or strongly) include counting to infinity (1 ⇒ 2 ⇒ 3 ⇒ ...) and loops such as the transformation function of the Collatz conjecture (1 ⇒ 2 ⇒ 4 ⇒ 1 ⇒ ..., it is an open problem if there are any other loops of the Collatz transformation).
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Another example is the single-rule system { *r*(*x*,*y*) → *r*(*y*,*x*) }, which has no normalizing properties since from any term, e.g.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] *r*(4,2) a single rewrite sequence starts, viz.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] This leads to the idea of rewriting "modulo commutativity" where a term is in normal form if no rules but commutativity apply.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] The system {*b* → *a*, *b* → *c*, *c* → *b*, *c* → *d*} (pictured) is an example of a weakly normalizing but not strongly normalizing system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] *a* and *d* are normal forms, and *b* and *c* can be reduced to *a* or *d*, but the infinite reduction *b* → *c* → *b* → *c* → ... means that neither *b* nor *c* is strongly normalizing.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] The pure untyped lambda calculus does not satisfy the strong normalization property, and not even the weak normalization property.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Consider the term $\lambda x.xxx$ (application is left associative).
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Therefore, the term $(\lambda x.xxx)(\lambda x.xxx)$ is not strongly normalizing.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] And this is the only reduction sequence, hence it is not weakly normalizing either.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Various systems of typed lambda calculus including the simply typed lambda calculus, Jean-Yves Girard's System F, and Thierry Coquand's calculus of constructions are strongly normalizing.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A lambda calculus system with the normalization property can be viewed as a programming language with the property that every program terminates.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] Although this is a very useful property, it has a drawback: a programming language with the normalization property cannot be Turing complete, otherwise one could solve the halting problem by seeing if the program type checks.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] This means that there are computable functions that cannot be defined in the simply typed lambda calculus, and similarly for the calculus of constructions and System F.
[src:confluence-rewriting/normal-form-abstract-rewriting] A typical example is that of a self-interpreter in a total programming language.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In mathematics, linguistics, computer science, and logic, **rewriting** covers a wide range of methods of replacing subterms of a formula with other terms.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Such methods may be achieved by **rewriting systems** (also known as **rewrite systems**, **rewrite engines**, or **reduction systems**).
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In their most basic form, they consist of a set of objects, plus relations on how to transform those objects.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] One rule to rewrite a term could be applied in many different ways to that term, or more than one rule could be applicable.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Rewriting systems then do not provide an algorithm for changing one term to another, but a set of possible rule applications.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] When combined with an appropriate algorithm, however, rewrite systems can be viewed as computer programs, and several theorem provers and declarative programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In logic, the procedure for obtaining the conjunctive normal form (CNF) of a formula can be implemented as a rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For each rule, each variable denotes a subexpression, and the symbol ( $\to$ ) indicates that an expression matching the left hand side of it can be rewritten to one matching the right hand side of it.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In such a system, each rule is a logical equivalence, so performing a rewrite on an expression by these rules does not change the truth value of it.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Other useful rewriting systems in logic may not preserve truth values, see e.g. equisatisfiability.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Term rewriting systems can be employed to compute arithmetic operations on natural numbers.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] To this end, each such number has to be encoded as a term.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The simplest encoding is the one used in the Peano axioms, based on the constant 0 (zero) and the successor function *S*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For example, the numbers 0, 1, 2, and 3 are represented by the terms 0, S(0), S(S(0)), and S(S(S(0))), respectively.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The following term rewriting system can then be used to compute sum and product of given natural numbers.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] where the notation above each arrow indicates the rule used for each rewrite.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] where the last step comprises the previous example computation.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In linguistics, phrase structure rules, also called **rewrite rules**, are used in some systems of generative grammar, as a means of generating the grammatically correct sentences of a language.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Such a rule typically takes the form ${\rm {A\rightarrow X}}$ , where A is a syntactic category label, such as noun phrase or sentence, and X is a sequence of such labels or morphemes, expressing the fact that A can be replaced by X in generating the constituent structure of a sentence.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For example, the rule ${\rm {S\rightarrow NP\ VP}}$ means that a sentence can consist of a noun phrase (NP) followed by a verb phrase (VP); further rules will specify what sub-constituents a noun phrase and a verb phrase can consist of, and so on.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] From the above examples, it is clear that we can think of rewriting systems in an abstract manner.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] We need to specify a set of objects and the rules that can be applied to transform them.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The most general (unidimensional) setting of this notion is called an *abstract reduction system* or *abstract rewriting system* (abbreviated *ARS*).
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An ARS is simply a set *A* of objects, together with a binary relation → on *A* called the *reduction relation*, *rewrite relation* or just *reduction*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The word problem for an ARS is determining, given *x* and *y*, whether $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An object *x* in *A* is called *reducible* if there exists some other *y* in *A* such that $x\rightarrow y$ ; otherwise it is called *irreducible* or a normal form.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An object *y* is called a "normal form of *x*" if $x{\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ , and *y* is irreducible.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] If the normal form of *x* is unique, then this is usually denoted with $x{\downarrow }$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] If every object has at least one normal form, the ARS is called *normalizing*. $x\downarrow y$ or *x* and *y* are said to be *joinable* if there exists some *z* with the property that $x{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}z{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}y$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An ARS is said to possess the Church–Rosser property if $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An ARS is confluent if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}w{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An ARS is *locally confluent* if and only if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x\leftarrow w\rightarrow y$ implies $x{\mathbin {\downarrow }}y$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] An ARS is said to be *terminating* or *noetherian* if there is no infinite chain $x_{0}\rightarrow x_{1}\rightarrow x_{2}\rightarrow \cdots$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A confluent and terminating ARS is called *convergent* or *canonical*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Important theorems for abstract rewriting systems are that an ARS is confluent iff it has the Church–Rosser property, Newman's lemma (a terminating ARS is confluent if and only if it is locally confluent), and that the word problem for an ARS is undecidable in general.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A *string rewriting system* (SRS), also known as *semi-Thue system*, exploits the free monoid structure of the strings (words) over an alphabet to extend a rewriting relation, R , to *all* strings in the alphabet that contain left- and respectively right-hand sides of some rules as substrings.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Formally a semi-Thue system is a tuple $(\Sigma ,R)$ where $\Sigma$ is a (usually finite) alphabet, and R is a binary relation between some (fixed) strings in the alphabet, called the set of *rewrite rules*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The *one-step rewriting relation* ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ induced by R on $\Sigma ^{*}$ is defined as: if $s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ are any strings, then $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ if there exist $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ such that $s=xuy$ , $t=xvy$ , and $uRv$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Since ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ is a relation on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the pair $(\Sigma ^{*},{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }})$ fits the definition of an abstract rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Since the empty string is in $\Sigma ^{*}$ , R is a subset of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] If the relation R is symmetric, then the system is called a *Thue system*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In a SRS, the reduction relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ is compatible with the monoid operation, meaning that $x{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}y$ implies $uxv{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}uyv$ for all strings $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Similarly, the reflexive transitive symmetric closure of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ , denoted ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ , is a congruence, meaning it is an equivalence relation (by definition) and it is also compatible with string concatenation.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is called the *Thue congruence* generated by R .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In a Thue system, i.e. if R is symmetric, the rewrite relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ coincides with the Thue congruence ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The notion of a semi-Thue system essentially coincides with the presentation of a monoid.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Since ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is a congruence, we can define the factor monoid ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}=\Sigma ^{*}/{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ of the free monoid $\Sigma ^{*}$ by the Thue congruence.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] If a monoid ${\mathcal {M}}$ is isomorphic with ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}$ , then the semi-Thue system $(\Sigma ,R)$ is called a monoid presentation of ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] We immediately get some very useful connections with other areas of algebra.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For example, the alphabet $\{a,b\}$ with the rules $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon ,ba\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , where $\varepsilon$ is the empty string, is a presentation of the free group on one generator.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] If instead the rules are just $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , then we obtain a presentation of the bicyclic monoid.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Thus semi-Thue systems constitute a natural framework for solving the word problem for monoids and groups.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In fact, every monoid has a presentation of the form $(\Sigma ,R)$ , i.e. it may always be presented by a semi-Thue system, possibly over an infinite alphabet.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The word problem for a semi-Thue system is undecidable in general; this result is sometimes known as the *Post–Markov theorem*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A **term rewriting system** (**TRS**) is a rewriting system whose objects are *terms*, which are expressions with nested sub-expressions.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For example, the system shown under *§ Logic* above is a term rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The terms in this system are composed of binary operators $(\vee )$ and $(\wedge )$ and the unary operator $(\neg )$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Also present in the rules are variables, which represent any possible term (though a single variable always represents the same term throughout a single rule).
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In contrast to string rewriting systems, whose objects are sequences of symbols, the objects of a term rewriting system form a term algebra.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A term can be visualized as a tree of symbols, the set of admitted symbols being fixed by a given signature.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] As a formalism, term rewriting systems have the full power of Turing machines, that is, every computable function can be defined by a term rewriting system.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Some programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] One such example is Pure, a functional programming language for mathematical applications.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A *rewrite rule* is a pair of terms, commonly written as $l\rightarrow r$ , to indicate that the left-hand side *l* can be replaced by the right-hand side *r*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A *term rewriting system* is a set *R* of such rules.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A rule $l\rightarrow r$ can be *applied* to a term *s* if the left term l matches some subterm of *s*, that is, if there is some substitution $\sigma$ such that the subterm of s rooted at some position *p* is the result of applying the substitution $\sigma$ to the term l.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The subterm matching the left hand side of the rule is called a **redex** or **reducible expression**.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] The result term *t* of this rule application is then the result of replacing the subterm at position *p* in *s* by the term r with the substitution $\sigma$ applied, see picture 1.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] In this case, s is said to be *rewritten in one step*, or *rewritten directly*, to t by the system R , formally denoted as $s\rightarrow _{R}t$ , $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ , or as $s{\overset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ by some authors.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] A term rewriting given by a set R of rules can be viewed as an abstract rewriting system as defined above, with terms as its objects and ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ as its rewrite relation.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For example, $x*(y*z)\rightarrow (x*y)*z$ is a rewrite rule, commonly used to establish a normal form with respect to the associativity of * .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] That rule can be applied at the numerator in the term ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ with the matching substitution $\{x\mapsto a,\;y\mapsto a+1,\;z\mapsto a+2\}$ , see picture 2.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Applying that substitution to the rule's right-hand side yields the term $(a*(a+1))*(a+2)$ , and replacing the numerator by that term yields ${\frac {(a*(a+1))*(a+2)}{1*(2*3)}}$ , which is the result term of applying the rewrite rule.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Altogether, applying the rewrite rule has achieved what is called "applying the associativity law for * to ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ " in elementary algebra.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Alternately, the rule could have been applied to the denominator of the original term, yielding ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{(1*2)*3}}$ .
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Termination issues of rewrite systems in general are handled in *Abstract rewriting system#Termination and convergence*.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] For term rewriting systems in particular, the following additional subtleties are to be considered.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Termination even of a system consisting of one rule with a linear left-hand side is undecidable.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Termination is also undecidable for systems using only unary function symbols; however, it is decidable for finite ground systems.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] All these properties are satisfied by Toyama's examples.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] See Rewrite order and Path ordering (term rewriting) for ordering relations used in termination proofs for term rewriting systems.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Higher-order rewriting systems are a generalization of first-order term rewriting systems to lambda terms, allowing higher order functions and bound variables.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Various results about first-order TRSs can be reformulated for HRSs as well.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Graph rewrite systems are another generalization of term rewrite systems, operating on graphs instead of (ground-) terms / their corresponding tree representation.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Trace theory provides a means for discussing multiprocessing in more formal terms, such as via the trace monoid and the history monoid.
[src:confluence-rewriting/termination-term-rewriting] Rewriting can be performed in trace systems as well.
